- CDK/Material: 16.2.2
- Browser(s): Chrome & Firefox
- Operating System (e.g. Windows, macOS, Ubuntu): MacOs
- Angular-Matrial: 16.2.8

### Feature Description

When a slider has a range from a negative to a positive (-45 to +45 as an example) the slider thumb can be centered at the zero mark but the track still gets drawn from the left side. The track should be drawn from the zero mark in each direction

<img width="119" alt="image" src="https://github.com/angular/components/assets/16738284/858a25be-7303-483e-bea2-721edb68b66b">
<img width="107" alt="image" src="https://github.com/angular/components/assets/16738284/a0284b1b-677e-4c1e-acff-58c896a71099">

I am currently using a directive to hack the slider to do this

```
@Directive({
  selector: 'mat-slider[ngxCenterOnZero]',
  standalone: true,
})
export class NgxCenterOnZeroDirective implements OnInit {
  #slider = inject(MatSlider, { self: true });

  ngOnInit(): void {
    this.#slider._updateTrackUI = (source: MatSliderThumb) => {
      // where is the zero value as a percentage on the rack
      const centerPercent = 0 - source.min / (source.max - source.min);
      const fillPercentage = source.fillPercentage - centerPercent;
      this.#slider._setTrackActiveStyles({
        left: `${centerPercent * 100}%`,
        right: 'auto',
        transformOrigin: 'left',
        transform: `scaleX(${fillPercentage})`,
      });
    };
  }
}
```



### Use Case

Well, it would make the slider more useful and be a better user experience
